that coverage remains active!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing class accessibility**\\n\\nI'm running into issues with using `Class.newInstance` because it can't instantiate a package-private class from a different package, leading to an `IllegalAccessException`. Creating a public top-level class in a separate file might help, but I worry about violating the one-to-one mapping for generated test class files. I wonder if making it nested and static would work instead. It seems I could use `java.lang.Object` as an invalid provider to bypass reflection issues, but that introduces other complexities with null class loaders. I need to figure this out!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reviewing JUnit test class requirements**\\n\\nI'm considering that a JUnit test class has an implicit public no-argument constructor if there's no explicit constructor defined. This is beneficial because it avoids the issues with using nested classes and reflection metadata. The FactoryFinder can access the public test class within the `javax.ws.rs` package using `Class.newInstance()` without a problem. However, if I use the same class as an invalid provider, it ends up instantiating a new test class instead of the intended `RuntimeDelegate`. I need to ensure the constructor is set up correctly!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Preparing for a test**\\n\\nIt sounds like I need to use AssertJ's `catchThrowable` method to catch any Throwable types. I'll probably go with a static import for convenience. I'm considering naming the test something like `reportsLinkageDetailsWhenProviderIsNotRuntimeDelegate`. It's crucial to verify that the `RuntimeDelegate` cache starts as null and resets properly afterward. Before I run the test, I should set the instance to null and check the git status to ensure everything is good to go.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_YC7mLaqTidhBTGcULvu6boLl|fc_0ed3c25c7e658cc80169f10e95ba2c819fa2a46c543e4655d1", "name": "bash